The Overgrown Ruins~
Stone walls of considerable age emerge from the earth here, their dressed-stone surfaces cracked and separated by tree roots that have inserted themselves into every joint over the centuries.
The ruins are extensive, spreading in multiple directions, and the @@gancient stonework@@N is visible in fragments -- a carved lintel here, a column base there -- beneath thick layers of @@Gmoss and vine@@N.
Whatever this complex was, it was large and intended to be permanent; the quantity of worked stone visible from this point alone implies a structure whose original footprint rivaled a small town.
The forest has not destroyed it so much as redistributed it, incorporating the stone into its own structure, and the ruins and the living wood have reached an accommodation that neither side acknowledges.
At the center of the ruin complex, somewhere to the south, a corroded iron gate still marks the boundary of what was once the inner courtyard, its hinges intact after all these centuries.
